	     <tr><td colspan=2 align=right class=mform id=fs8>1 Replies</td></tr>
	     </form></table><tr><td colspan=2><ul><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99233298969356>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=3&mid=99233298969356>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=99233298969356>RE: New Monk</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=99233298969356#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Tue, Jun 12th 4:03 AM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=39551><span id=Guru>Osano</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>171 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [4.24]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>The argument about starting points has *always* been hot and heavy.&nbsp;&nbsp;There are decent arguments for dumping all your points into STR, AGI, or STA.  Even DEX has its supporters.<br><br>STR -- Better damage, a key Monk attribute.<br>AGI -- Better AC, a monk weakness.<br>STA -- Better HP, another monk weakness.<br>DEX -- Better skill-up rate, and better proc rate on weapons with effects.<br><br>Before giving my opinion, I'll tell you the bottom line:  It really doesn't matter all that much.  By picking and choosing your armor set, you can deal with just about any starting set of attributes.  Plus, the effect of 5 extra points here and there is really marginal.  The only one of the above which I think is a clear mistake is all DEX.<br><br>What I did:  Put 5 points in each.  Being brand new to EQ, but having played specialty fighter types for all my Roleplaying game life, I chose Monk (and very happy about that choice).  Not knowing any better, and not wanting to make any really HUGE mistakes, I just balanced it.  It turns out this is not a bad way to go.<br><br>Given hindsight, what I would have done:  Put 15 points into STA and 5 into STR.  Your HP bonus due to STA is increasingly large at higher levels. It can make a BIG difference.  When, as a lower level monk, I read posts recommending STA as the place to go, I thought that was stupid.  It's not.  Plus, it's the hardest stat to increase with equipment suitable for a monk.<br><br>There is a *lot* of AGI/DEX equipment for monks, so getting those up is really easy.  STR equipment is not so hard to come by either, but it's important to get it over 100, and the 5 extra points there helps.  That's why I make the recommendation that I do.<br><br>Is there anything wrong with +20 STR? Not at all, it's actually a highly recommended way to go.  Certainly no reason to ditch your monk, and better than +10 STR, +10 AGI in my opinion.  Just target AGI over STR for your equipment (very easy to do) and you'll be happy, I'm sure.<br><br>P.S. Forget EQ'lizer for monk advice.  www.monkly-business.com is awesome, but tends to be geared toward the higher end.  This is a great spot to post, with a number of regulars who like to answer questions, especially geared toward lower/mid levels.  You can take advice from people like Keyeluke or GLASS (especially for Iksar questions) and I hope myself with a good assurance of accuracy.</p>&nbsp;<br>Osano<br>Level 44 Human Monk<br>Tholuxe-Paells</td></td></tr>
	     <tr><td colspan=2 align=right class=mform id=fs8>1 Replies</td></tr>
	     </form></table><tr><td colspan=2><ul><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99235129880989>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=3&mid=99235129880989>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=99235129880989>RE: New Monk</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=99235129880989#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Tue, Jun 12th 9:08 AM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=35651><span id=Guru>Keyeluke</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>678 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.30]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>This question is the one I researched most heavily before I started my monk.&nbsp;&nbsp;I put 10 into Agi, 5 Str, 3 Sta, 2 Dex.  Do I regret this choice?  No.  Do I think, in retrospect, that it was the best choice?  No. The worst choice?  No.<br><br>Will it make or break your monk?<br><br>No.<br><br>I did fine through my early and mid levels with the distribution I chose.  You'll do fine no matter how you distribute.  Each approach has its benefits and its proponents.  Osano covered the pros and cons very well.  My two cp worth of advice is to make an informed decision, then move on and don't worry about it any more.  Not only will your choices in gear have a greater effect on your character in the long run, but you'll see that there are more important things than stats.<br><br>At this stage of my life, the consensus seems to be that gear should be prioritized as follows:<br><br>1) AC First and Foremost (Never give up AC for stats)<br>2) Resists<br>3) HP<br>4) Stats<br><br>I had a lot of stat gear a while back.  I've slowly given up a decent amount of it in favor of AC gear.  Now my AC is good, my resists are getting better (nice to resist a 250 or 500 point DD every so often), and my stats are nothing special.  In a few more levels I'll be able to start doing the quests for the really good gear that gives both AC and stats, but for now my unbuffed stats are probably worse than those of many level 25-30 monks.  Doesn't really matter that much.  The buffs you will routinely get at higher levels will make how you distribute your 20 initial points pretty much irrelevant.  For example, a little while back I was fighting with a group in Dreadlands, and with buffs my str sta and agi were 150s or higher and my dex was 255.  You won't see these numbers for a while, but you WILL see stat buffs aplenty as you group, even at low levels.<br><br>If I had to do it again?  I'd probably go 10 Str 10 Sta.  Agi is overrated IMO, and you can get Agi gear AND Agi buffs very easily.  Dex is nice when training up your weapons skills and helping procs, but if you don't have a proc'ing weapon you don't seem to need it all that much other than at the beginning of each level.  Str helps your attack number directly, as well as your damage output.  Sta helps not only your HP, but will keep your endurance up during long melees (a real issue if you're swinging something even somewhat heavy).  I had the same reaction as Osano when I heard all STA - thought it was ludicrous.  I still wouldn't go all STA, but I see the merits of the argument clearly now.<br><br>Keyeluke <br>Monk of the Silent Fist, 45th Circle <br>Strange Brew <br>Druzzil Ro<br></p>&nbsp;<br>Keyeluke<br>Member of Tenacity - Druzzil Ro<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=27415" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=27415</a></td></td></tr>
