	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=39551><span id=Guru>Osano</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>171 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [4.21]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>The best thing to do is SAVE your points for higher levels.&nbsp;&nbsp;All your early skills go up quite easily with regular use -- H2H, 1HB, 2HB, offense, defense, etc.  The only starting skill worth priming at all is Sense Heading because it just goes up so damn slow for the first 10 points.  Still, if you have the patience to keep mashing the SH button, save those points too.  Put exactly ONE point into all the skills you get between levels 1 and 17, just to get your initial training in each new skill.<br><br>You'll be glad later when you get FD, ID, and the higher level special attacks that you have lots of training points to spend.  Now, I didn't do it this way (wish I had) because I just bombed right into the game and blew training points all over the place.<br><br>At 5 points per level, you'll have about 80 points by the time you reach level 17.  Dump 40 into FD and save yourself a TON of practice.  This leaves you with about 45 points for ID when you hit level 18.  Dump all of them into that.  Note that this will cost you a little cash, as they start charging for training above a certain level, but it shouldn't be all that much up to skill 65 or so.<br><br>Then, keep saving points for Eagle Strike (level 20), Dragon Punch/Tail Rake (level 25), and Flying Kick (level 30).  Dump all the points you have into each one when you get it.  This will prime the attack so that you start doing decent damage with it right away.<br><br>After level 30, there's not much use for training points unless you want to prime some tradeskills or languages or whatever, so have fun with those.<br><br>Good Luck with your new monk.</p>&nbsp;<br>Osano<br>Level 44 Human Monk<br>Tholuxe-Paells</td></td></tr>
